LANGUAGE: TypeScript
PACKAGE_MANAGER: yarn install
WORKING_COMMANDS: yarn install, yarn build, yarn test
SOURCE_DIRECTORIES: src/
BUILD_OUTPUT: *.min.js, *.min.js.map, types/ (do NOT edit these directly)

RULES:
- ONLY edit files in SOURCE_DIRECTORIES (src/) — never edit build output directly
- Build output is gitignored and must NOT be committed
- Run the build command after making changes to verify they compile
- ALWAYS write tests for your changes. If no test framework is set up, install one appropriate for the language (e.g. vitest/jest for JS/TS, pytest for Python, cargo test for Rust) and create the test file. Tests should verify the specific behavior your change introduces or fixes.
- If you add a test framework or test script, update .github/workflows/ci.yml to run the tests (e.g. add a "yarn test" or "npm test" step after the build step)
- Run tests and make sure they pass before finishing
- If your fix changes how users install or use the library, update the README accordingly
- Keep changes minimal and surgical — fix only what the issue asks for
- ONLY commit files directly related to the fix — no debug scripts, temp files, or scratch code
- Delete any files you created for debugging or testing purposes (e.g. debug-test.js, test-scratch.py) before finishing
- Do NOT add or modify config files (vitest.config.ts, jest.config.js, tsconfig.json, .eslintrc) unless the issue specifically requires test infrastructure or config changes
- Before finishing, run git status and remove any untracked files that are not part of the fix

KNOWN_RISKS:
- Complex rollup build process with Google Closure Compiler - build failures may be cryptic
- WebWorker implementation uses dynamic imports that must be handled carefully
- jsqr-es6 dependency is imported via relative path in worker.ts - path changes will break builds
- Camera access testing requires user permission and real browser environment

QUIRKS:
- Build creates multiple output variants (ES6, UMD, legacy) with different optimization levels
- Worker script is inlined into legacy build but external for others  
- TypeScript declarations are generated separately via tsc, not rollup
- Demo page expects build output files to be present in root directory
- Package.json references build output in "files" array for npm publishing